* Power Outages

- Disrupt communications, water and transport
- Close retail businesses such as groceries, gas, ATM, bank etc.
- Cause food/medicine spoilage and water contamination

How to Prepare

- Take inventory of the items you need that rely on electricity Plan for batteries and other alternatives to meet your needs
- Talk to your doctor about a plan for medical devices powered by elec and refrigerated medicines - how long can they be stored at higher temperatures and get specific guidance on life critical medications
- Sign up for local alerts and warning systems, monitor weather reports
- Install carbon monoxide detectors with battery backup
- Determine whether your home phone will work in a power outage and how long battery backup will last
- have enough nonperishable food and water
- Keep mobile phones and other elec equipment charged and gas tanks full.

Survive During

- Keep freezers and fridges closed, the fridge will keep food for about four hours, a full freezer will keep the temp for about 48 hours. Use coolers and ice. Monitor temps with thermometer.
- Generators, camp stoves, or charcoal grills should always be used outdoors and at least 20 feet away from windows. Never use gastop stove or oven to heat your home.Avoid carbon monoxide poisoning.
- Check on your neighbors, older adults and young children are especially vulnerable to extreme temperatures
- Go to a community location with power if heat or cold is extreme
- Turn off or disconnect appliances, equipment, or electronics. Power may return with momentary "surges" or "spikes" that can cause damage.

What to do after

- When in doubt - throw it out. Any food that has been exposed to temps of 40 degrees or higher for two hours or more, or has unusual odor color or texture
- If the power is out for more than a day, discard any medication that should be refrigerated unless the drugs label says otherwise. If a life depends on refrigerated drugs, consult a doctor or pharmacist and use medicine only until a new supply is available.


